Tammy Petersen, News24(File, Nielen de Klerk, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - Rashied Staggie and three accomplices were allegedly found in possession of expensive whisky and cigars worth millions of rands, apparently stolen from a Johannesburg container depot last week.The contraband found in Thursday&rsquo;s arrest on the N1 was believed to have come from two containers stolen from Cleveland between April 10 and 18, Lieutenant Lloyd Ramovha said.Also in the group&rsquo;s possession were three unlicensed guns and ammunition.The Hawks arrested the men, aged between 20 and 60, after a convoy of three "luxurious" vehicles was pulled over near Canal Walk.Police were only willing to confirm that one of the men was a "well-known former inmate and gang leader in the Cape Flats", who was out on parole.A well-placed source confirmed that Staggie was among those apprehended.Staggie, once the leader of the Hard Livings gang, was granted full parole in 2014 after serving 13 years behind bars for a burglary at the Faure police armoury.Pagad members killed his brother Rashaad, who also held a top rank in the gang, in 1996. He&nbsp;was shot and set alight in Salt River.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.